  "local_port": 44152,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are famous places in Rajasthan?",
  "response": "Rajasthan, often referred to as the \"Land of Kings,\" is a state in northern India known for its rich history, vibrant culture, and architectural marvels. Here are some of the most famous places to visit in Rajasthan:\n\n### 1. **Jaipur (The Pink City)**\n   - **Amber Fort**: A stunning hilltop fort with intricate architecture and panoramic views.\n   - **Hawa Mahal**: Known as the \"Palace of Winds,\" this iconic structure features a unique honeycomb design.\n   - **City Palace**: A grand complex featuring a blend of Mughal and Rajasthani architecture.\n   - **Jantar Mantar**: A UNESCO World Heritage Site, this is an astronomical observatory built by Maharaja Jai Singh II.\n\n### 2. **Udaipur (The City of Lakes)**\n   - **Lake Pichola**: A picturesque lake with the Lake Palace and Jag Mandir island palaces.\n   - **City Palace**: A sprawling palace complex overlooking Lake Pichola.\n   - **Jag Mandir**: An island palace with beautiful gardens and architecture.\n   - **Saheliyon-ki-Bari**: A serene garden with fountains, lotus pools, and marble pavilions.\n\n### 3. **Jodhpur (The Blue City)**\n   - **Mehrangarh Fort**: One of the largest forts in India, offering breathtaking views of the blue city.\n   - **Umaid Bhawan Palace**: A part of this grand palace is still a royal residence, while another section serves as a luxury hotel.\n   - **Jaswant Thada**: A beautiful marble memorial commemorating Maharaja Jaswant Singh II.\n\n### 4. **Jaisalmer (The Golden City)**\n   - **Jaisalmer Fort**: A living fort with shops, hotels, and residences within its walls.\n   - **Patwon Ki Haveli**: A cluster of five havelis (mansions) known for their intricate carvings.\n   - **Sam Sand Dunes**: A popular spot for camel safaris and experiencing the Thar Desert.\n\n### 5. **Pushkar**\n   - **Pushkar Lake**: A sacred lake surrounded by over 500 temples and ghats.\n   - **Brahma Temple**: One of the few temples in the world dedicated to Lord Brahma.\n   - **Pushkar Camel Fair**: An annual festival featuring camel races, cultural performances, and more.\n\n### 6. **Ranthambore**\n   - **Ranthambore National Park**: A renowned tiger reserve offering wildlife safaris.\n   - **Ranthambore Fort**: A historic fort located within the national park.\n\n### 7. **Bikaner**\n   - **Junagarh Fort**: An impressive fort with a rich history and beautiful architecture.\n   - **Karni Mata Temple (Rat Temple)**: A unique temple home to thousands of rats.\n   - **Lallgarh Palace**: A grand palace built by Maharaja Ganga Singh, now a heritage hotel.\n\n### 8. **Chittorgarh**\n   - **Chittorgarh Fort**: Another UNESCO World Heritage Site, this is the largest fort in India with a rich history of Rajput valor.\n   - **Vijay Stambh (Victory Tower)**: A towering structure built to commemorate a military victory.\n\n### 9. **Mount Abu**\n   - **Dilwara Temples**: Renowned for their exquisite marble carvings, these Jain temples are a marvel of architecture.\n   - **Nakki Lake**: A scenic lake surrounded by hills and gardens.\n   - **Mount Abu Wildlife Sanctuary**: A sanctuary known for its lush greenery and diverse wildlife.\n\n### 10. **Bundi**\n   - **Bundi Palace**: A palace known for its frescoes and murals.\n   - **Taragarh Fort**: A historic fort offering panoramic views of the town.\n   - **Stepwells (Baoris)**: Intricately designed stepwells that are architectural marvels.\n\nThese are just a few of the many incredible destinations in Rajasthan. Each place offers a unique glimpse into the state's rich heritage, making it a must-visit for anyone interested in history, culture, and architecture.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
